Description of the holotype .
Colourless; body length 396 µm; eye spots present before mounting. Entire body surface closely ornamented: numerous small tubercles are present (
Fig. 5 A–C
), most of which are rounded and fairly uniform in size (diameter up to 2 µm); the tubercles are spaced very densely (or in contact) and form transverse lines (
Fig. 5 B, C
) but without a reticular design. The ornamentation, also present on the legs, is less visible on the ventral body surface.

The claws, of the
Isohypsibius
type , are well developed and have a long common basal portion and a wide proximal portion to both main and secondary branches (
Fig. 5 D, E
). The orientation in the slide made the measurements of the total claw length difficult and for this reason we have included separate measurements for the main branch length. The orientation of the holotype meant we were only able to measure the claws of the first pair of legs and the claws of the hind legs (
Table 1
). Main branches with accessory points (
Fig. 5 E
). Small, flexible lunules present (
Fig. 5 E
). Cuticular bars on the legs absent.
